## Network Connectivity

Cross-boundary routes ({{ pct_cross_la|round(1) }}%) are critical for regional connectivity but create governance fragmentation: no single LTA has full authority over route planning, subsidy decisions, or performance monitoring. This fragmentation is a structural weakness of the post-deregulation framework.

The Bus Services Act 2025 partially addresses this through Combined Authority powers and the potential for multi-LTA Enhanced Partnerships. However, for LTAs without combined authority status, cross-boundary routes remain dependent on bilateral agreements that are vulnerable to budget pressures on either side.

## Dead-End vs Through Routes

Routes that terminate within a single LTA boundary typically serve local access functions — connecting residential areas to town centres, employment sites, and transport interchanges. Cross-boundary routes serve strategic functions — connecting LSOAs to regional labour markets and services that are absent locally.

Policy interventions targeting connectivity gaps should distinguish between these two functions: local access gaps require different interventions (DRT, community transport) than strategic connectivity gaps (frequency enhancement on cross-boundary routes, integration with rail interchange).

## Policy Implications

The {{ pct_cross_la|round(1) }}% cross-boundary route share provides a measure of how "joined up" the network is. Higher cross-boundary share correlates with better access to regional opportunities but also greater governance complexity. LTAs pursuing Bus Service Improvement Plans should explicitly map cross-boundary dependencies and include co-funding agreements with neighbouring authorities where relevant.

*Methodology: Route geometry from BODS GTFS shapes.txt (7,241 routes with geometry, 53.1% of total). Cross-LA classification via spatial intersection with ONS LAD boundaries. Mean length computed from Haversine distances between stops where shape_dist_traveled was null (100% of cases).*
